article.headline: Warrick has double-double in victory
article.linkText: No. 25 Syracuse rallies to edge Rutgers
article.story: SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) -- Hakim Warrick had 16 points and 14 rebounds and Jeremy McNeil came off the bench to key a late rally, leading Syracuse (No. 25 ESPN/USA Today) to a 63-61 victory over Rutgers Tuesday night. The Orangemen (15-5, 5-4 Big East) were desperate for a win. They were coming off road losses last week to Providence and Connecticut and had lost four of five to fall out of the AP Top 25 for the first time in a year. Rutgers (13-8, 5-6), which was coming off an 85-58 loss to Seton Hall after winning four straight in conference, has never won a game in the Carrier Dome since joining the Big East in the 1995-96 season. But the Scarlet Knights came close as Syracuse played without point guard Billy Edelin, who did not dress for the game. Coach Jim Boeheim declined to comment on Edelin, who had missed two of the previous three games but had been on the bench. Boeheim said a statement on Edelin would be released Wednesday. Josh Pace and Craig Forth each scored 12 points and Gerry McNamara had 10 for Syracuse. Ricky Shields hit six 3-pointers and scored 20 points to lead Rutgers. Herve Lamizana had 14 points and eight rebounds and Marquis Webb had 11 points. Quincy Douby, who was averaging 11.5 points per game, did not score in 16 minutes of play. Trailing 30-23 at halftime, the Scarlet Knights went on a 20-6 run early in the second half to go ahead for only the second time in the game. Webb hit a 3 to start the spurt and a three-point play by Adrian Hill gave Rutgers a 38-37 lead at 13:15. Two free throws by Lamizana and a 3 from the right corner by Shields extended the margin to 43-38. Warrick and McNeil then led the Orangemen back. Warrick fed McNeil for a layup off the glass that tied it at 46 with 7:41 left and Pace followed his own miss to give Syracuse the lead for good. McNeil then hit two free throws and his dunk off a nice feed in the lane from McNamara made it 54-49 at 4:17. The Scarlet Knights had more than one chance in the final 66 seconds to send it to overtime. Trailing 61-58, they watched McNamara, who had hit all 23 of his free throws in the conference entering the game, miss the front end of a 1-and-1 with 42 seconds left. And when Warrick did the same thing 17 seconds later, the Scarlet Knights had new life. But Douby, the Big East's leading 3-point shooter at 50 percent who hit 14-of-18 during a two-week stretch in January, missed twice from long range. Two free throws by Warrick with 4.5 seconds to go allowed Syracuse to escape when Shields hit a long 3 at the buzzer to boost his career points total to 1,005.
